===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*wert-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|werde}}, {{m|enm|wierde}}, {{m|enm|wirde}}, {{m|enm|wyrede}}, {{m|enm|wurde}}, from {{inh|en|ang|wyrd||fate}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wurdiz}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*wert-||to turn, wind}}. Cognate with {{cog|is|urður||fate}}. Related to {{cog|ang|weorþan||to become}}. {{doublet|en|wyrd}}. More at {{l|en|worth}}.

''Weird'' was extinct by the 16th century in English. It survived in {{bor|en|sco|-}}, whence Shakespeare borrowed it in naming the ''[[w:Weird Sisters|Weird Sisters]]'', reintroducing it to English. The senses "abnormal", "strange" etc. arose via reinterpretation of ''Weird Sisters'' and date from after this reintroduction.

